{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14011"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14011"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.27,0.26,0.09,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6660"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"9587"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after being diagnosed with hereditary haemochromatosis. He was screened for the condition after a sibling was diagnosed. He has commenced regular venesection therapy without issue. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications except for a general health multivitamin. He eats an unrestricted diet, exercises regularly, does not smoke and drinks three to four standard drinks of alcohol per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Recent laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum ferritin: 100 \u00b5g/L (30-300)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETransferrin saturation: 50% (20-55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT): 25 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase (AST): 30 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP): 80 U/L (30-120)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBilirubin: 15 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe asks if there are any lifestyle changes he should make in light of his haemochromatosis diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Avoid vitamin C containing foods","Abstain from alcohol completely","Avoid consuming raw shellfish","Increase calcium intake","Follow an iron-free diet"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor a patient with newly diagnosed haemochromatosis who has commenced venesection therapy, the most appropriate advice regarding further management of the options provided is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eavoid consuming raw shellfish\u003C/strong\u003E. This recommendation is primarily due to the increased risk of infection with \u003Cem\u003EVibrio vulnificus\u003C/em\u003E, a bacterium found in raw or undercooked seafood, particularly shellfish. The bacteria thrive in a high-iron environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollowing an iron-free diet\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not necessary for patients with haemochromatosis who are undergoing regular venesection. The venesection therapy is effective in removing excess iron, and complete dietary iron restriction is typically not required, although patients should be advised to not eat red meat daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoiding vitamin C-containing foods\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard recommendation for haemochromatosis patients. While vitamin C can increase iron absorption, patients undergoing regular venesection do not typically need to avoid eating vitamin C-containing foods but should moderate the amount. Patients should be counselled to avoid any vitamin supplements that contain vitamin C or iron, and this patient should be advised to check the content of his multivitamin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete alcohol abstinence\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessarily required for all haemochromatosis patients, especially those with normal liver function tests, as in this case. However, moderation is advised, and in patients with signs of liver injury abstinence is recommended. Excessive alcohol intake can exacerbate liver damage in haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific recommendation for haemochromatosis management. While calcium can interfere with iron absorption, this is not a primary strategy for managing the condition, especially in patients undergoing regular venesection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing haemochromatosis is regular venesection to reduce iron overload, along with monitoring of iron levels and organ function. Patients should also be educated about the potential complications of the disease and the importance of regular follow-up. While dietary restrictions are generally not necessary, avoiding raw shellfish is an important precaution to prevent potentially \u003Cem\u003EVibrio vulnificus\u003C/em\u003E infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venesection is the primary treatment for haemochromatosis to reduce iron overload.","Dietary restrictions are generally not necessary in haemochromatosis patients undergoing regular venesection.","However, patients with haemochromatosis should avoid consuming raw shellfish due to the risk of Vibrio vulnificus infection."],"references":["European Association for the Study of the Liver. EASL clinical practice guidelines on haemochromatosis. Journal of hepatology. 2022 Aug;77(2):479-502. Available at: https://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278(22)00211-2/fulltext","Bacon BR, Adams PC, Kowdley KV, Powell LW, Tavill AS; American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases. Diagnosis and management of hemochromatosis: 2011 practice guideline by the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases. Hepatology. 2011;54(1):328-343. doi:10.1002/hep.24330","Adams PC, Barton JC. How I treat hemochromatosis. Blood. 2010;116(3):317-325. doi:10.1182/blood-2010-01-261875"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14011"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T20:06:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T20:06:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6660"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53653"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"